title: High schools: Bishop Feehan edges Martha's Vineyard
text: Posted Oct. 4, 2015 at 9:41 PM By Cape Cod Times Posted Oct. 4, 2015 at 9:41 PM » Social News OAK BLUFFS -- Josh Cayer’s 26-yard field goal late in the second quarter provided the only points either team could muster, as the Bishop Feehan Shamrocks won a defensive football game against Martha’s Vineyard 3-0 on Sunday. The Vineyarders (2-2, 1-1 EAC) have now lost seven straight to Bishop Feehan (1-3, 1-0 EAC), getting shut out for the third time since 2009 against their Eastern Athletic Conference rival. “Great defensive effort on our part. Not so great offensive effort,” Martha’s Vineyard coach Donald Herman said. “We’ve always struggled to score points against Bishop Feehan.” Cayer’s field goal came with 34 seconds left in the second quarter. The Vineyarders’ defense stepped up in the second half and limited Bishop Feehan to just 50 yards of total offense, but Martha’s Vineyard couldn’t do much better when it had possession. Senior linebacker Austin Chandler led the defensive charge for the Vineyarders, recording 15 tackles overall and two for losses in his first game back from a knee injury. Senior Jacob Cardoza had an interception, and senior Ben Clark and sophomore Zachary Moreis each recovered a fumble. MONDAY’S GAME Sacred Heart at Nantucket 1:30 p.m. at Vito Capizzo Stadium, Nantucket Notes: Game moved from Friday and then Saturday night due to impending weather. Junior Travis Demby is coming off a Week 3 game against Holbrook/Avon in which he rushed for 96 yards and scored three times, upping his season total to four. FIELD HOCKEY Sandwich 1, Falmouth 0: Carly Whittle scored on a penalty stroke with 13 minutes left in the game to give the Blue Knights an Atlantic Coast League win over the Clippers in East Sandwich. Sandwich (6-1-1) goalie Anna Hurley recorded three saves and got great defense from Anne Davis to pick up her fifth shutout of the season. The Blue Knights had an 11-2 advantage in corners, but Falmouth (3-1-2) kept the game close thanks to three saves by goalie Molly Duff-Still and solid defense from left midfielder Jordan Willis. By Cape Cod Times
